<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Coffee Column</TITLE>
    <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0 beta 1">
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#e2cca0">
<H3><FONT FACE="Helvetica">A Seattle Weekly article titled<I> &quot;Bucks
vs. Starbucks: As Starbucks invades the East Coast will it be corrupted
by the natives?&quot;</I> was adapted (by the author) from this essay.</FONT></H3>
<BR>
<BR>
<P><CENTER><B><I><FONT SIZE=8 FACE="BEAGLE">A Meditation on Coffee <BR>
</FONT></I></B></CENTER>
<H4><CENTER><I>by Discovery Senior Fellow<BR>
Dr. Philip Gold<BR>
<BR>
</I><IMG SRC="fancy5.gif" WIDTH="455" HEIGHT="95" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"><BR>
</CENTER>
</H4>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H4><CENTER><I><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="BEAGLE"></I>In which it is pondered how
Starbucks, the Conquistadors of Coffee, headed east for the usual Conquistadorial
reasons - spread the faith, make some money, civilize the heathen - only
to discover a High Coffee Culture already in place: the Bucks County Coffee
Company. And thus began yet another exercise in mercantile multiculturalism,
with its attendant stresses and rewards.<I></FONT SIZE=4 FACE="BEAGLE"></I></CENTER>
</H4>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
</FONT><IMG SRC="yelstripe.gif" WIDTH="696" HEIGHT="4" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"0" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<BLOCKQUOTE>I learned about the Bucks County Coffee Company through the
younger sister of a former lover. She's a regional manager now. The sister,
not the lover (a Carter White House staffer now wed to a gentleman squire
farmer. We talk.) I did a magazine story on the company five years ago,
a favorable piece which duly impressed the boss of the sister of the lover,
and which garnered me a pass to their coffee nut &amp; chocolate warehouse
whenever I happen to visit Langhorne, Pa. I'll probably get another batch
of goodies out of this essay, but that's not why I'm writing it. I tell
myself. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Bucks got going in 1981, when Rodger Owen, a Navy veteran and bored executive,
bought a book on nuts, 25 pounds of cashews, and a little deep fat fryer
that he had a volunteer fireman rig up in his garage. After saturating his
primary market (the neighbors) he rented a 300 square foot carriage house
in downtown Yardley, Pa., conveniently near the town's only traffic light.
Rodger started advertising mail-order nuts in the <I>New Yorker</I> under
the name &quot;Squire's Choice&quot; (an unintended reference to the sister
of one of his future regional managers). He prospered, went into coffee,
named the new endeavor after its home, and today the Buck County coastal
empire boasts 42 stores, coffee houses, and kiosks from New Jersey to Washington,
DC. The coffee is good. The service is friendly. The Emperor presides. And,
until the arrival of the Conquistadors, there was peace.<BR>
<BR>
According to <I>Newsweek's</I> 18 September article, &quot;Not in My Backyard,&quot;
Starbucks has over 970 stores, with plans for 2,000 by 2000. But a popular
backlash may be developing, as non-northwest indigenous peoples struggle
to protect their local coffee cultures from the depredations and ravishments
of the newcomers. Indeed, if you believe a student columnist in <I>the Daily
Princetonian</I>, &quot;Starbucks is notorious for waiting for other coffee
shops to create a niche and then coming in with its sleazy old brand-name
recognition and usurping all the business.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Bucks has a coffeehouse/Internet caf&eacute; in Princeton. Starbucks recently
opened down the street. Still, since Bucks' Princeton facility attracts
far more townspeople than students, and since the author (a certain Snow
Tempest, '97, English major) never mentions Bucks, but does allude to &quot;Small
World Coffee&quot; and &quot;Harry's Luncheonette,&quot; one may assume
that she neither flacks for Bucks nor has access to their warehouse.<BR>
<BR>
Rodger Owen lacks Ms. Tempest's, well, tempestuousness. Indeed, he exudes
benign serenity and multicultural tact. Owen says that in the areas where
Bucks and Starbucks go bean-to-bean, he's holding his own. &quot;In many
ways, they're a good competitor. It's not like going against Wal-Mart. You're
not forced to compete on price.&quot; He knows that in some places Starbucks
has conducted saturation operations. Still, says Owen, &quot;Starbucks is
good for the business because they help build awareness of coffee.&quot;
Then he warns: &quot;Starbucks needs competition. People are fickle. If
Starbucks were the only [specialty] coffee purveyor, people will find another
beverage.&quot; <BR>
Concludes Mr. Owen: &quot;I have nothing but admiration for Starbucks. They
put out a quality product. They don't cut corners. Our biggest virtue is
that they're great and we're not them.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
How exquisitely multicultural. <I>They're great and we're not them</I>.
In fact, it's surprising how many ways Starbucks differs from its alternative-coastal
coffee competition. The eastern tribes generally prefer lighter roasts.
Starbucks roasts so darkly that some among the natives call it, &quot;Charbucks.&quot;
The eastern tribes like flavored coffees. Starbucks eschews such undeveloped
tastes. Starbucks sells mostly drop-in and carry-out beverages. Bucks earns
over half its money in bean sales, much of that bought in supermarket kiosks
that often double as real-reality chat rooms Starbucks has moved into milk-based
beverages. Bucks makes a mocha crush that can give a frappacino chills,
but still concentrates on the hot stuff, which it offers in a polystyrene
cup that, Rodger asserts, is both easier to handle and more environmentally
benign than Starbuck's finger-stinging paper.<BR>
<BR>
Yet none of this really captures the spiritual aspect of east coast coffee,
or suggests that Starbucks can operate for long in such hostile territory
without spiritual damage of its own. The eastern tribes live harried lives.
Rodger sells them moments of peace, quiet times in the morning and evening
when they withdraw into themselves with their mix of French Roast and Hazelnut
(two-thirds/one-third), or Costa Rica La Minita Estate, or Yemen Mocha Mattari,
or Amaretto, or Ethiopia Yirgacheffe. In fact, says Rodger, &quot;People
enjoy standing in line for their coffee. I've been criticized by some of
my landlords because my lines are too long. I tell them it's their morning
pause. And,&quot; he adds, &quot;maybe a chance to stand in line next to
some one interesting.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Bucks offers solace, communion, the call of the mini-retreat. Starbucks,
curiously, has taken on the frenetic quick-in/quick-out ambiance of the
eastern tribes. (Try DC's Dupont Circle and Georgetown locations if you
want to get jolted by more than caffeine.) It's as though the natives have
reserved their gentleness and grace for their own, meanwhile corrupting
the intruders with their coarser ways.<BR>
<BR>
If so, it wouldn't be the first time in history that Conquistadors found
themselves afflicted with the ills of the conquered. Nor would it be inappropriate
to suggest that some of the east coast's native remedies for incivility
and spiritual unease might have value here. If not as a civility therapy
(none needed, yet), then as an exercise in applied multiculturalism. Says
Rodger: &quot;Starbucks has come here. East coast coffee has never gone
west.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<B>Celebrate diversity, Seattle. Try some east coast coffee. </B></BLOCKQUOTE>
<B></B>
<H5><FONT COLOR=#800000 FACE="Helvetica">PHILIP GOLD LOVES STARBUCKS COFFEE,
BUT PREFERS IT IN A BUCKS COUNTY MUG. HE ALSO HAS BUCKS' 800 AND FAX NUMBERS.
TRY PGOLD@DISCOVERY.ORG. BEYOND KEEPING THE SAMPLES COMING, HE HAS NO ECONOMIC
INTEREST IN THE COMPANY.</FONT><FONT SIZE=2 COLOR=#800000></FONT> </H5>
