<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Clinton/Tyrrell review</TITLE>
    <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0 beta 1">
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#bdd2fd" LINK="#f80755">
<FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Helvetica">FROM <I>SEATTLE WEEKLY</I>, 2 OCTOBER 1996</FONT><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<H2><CENTER><FONT color="#0000ff"><FONT FACE="Palatino">Review of:<BR>
<I>Between Hope and History: Meeting America's Challenges for the 21<SUP>st</SUP>
Century&quot;</I><BR>
by President Bill Clinton</CENTER>
</H2>
<H4><CENTER><FONT FACE="Palatino">(Times Books, 1996)</CENTER>
</H4>
<H1><CENTER>&amp; </CENTER>
</H1>
<H2><CENTER>&quot;<I>Boy Clinton: The Political Biography</I>,&quot;<BR>
by R. Emmett Tyrrell, Jr. </CENTER>
</H2>
<H4><CENTER>(Regnery, 1996)</FONT color="#0000ff"></FONT FACE="Palatino"></CENTER>
</H4>
<P><CENTER></CENTER>
<P></FONT color="#0000ff">
<H5><CENTER>Reviewed by Discovery Senior Fellow<A HREF="gold.html"> Dr.
Philip Gold</A></FONT FACE="Palatino"><BR>
<BR>
<IMG SRC="starline2.gif" WIDTH="268" HEIGHT="20" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></CENTER>
</H5>
<H5></H4><FONT FACE="Palatino"><FONT SIZE=3>We have crafted an era as abhorrent
to the future as to the past. Bill Clinton's as good a symbol of that era
as any.<BR>
<BR>
When John Kennedy wanted to author a book that would help him toward the
white House, he assembled (with <I>mucho</I> assistance from my old Georgetown
colleague, Jules Davids) <I>Profiles in Courage</I>. Jimmy Clinton borrowed
Admiral Rickover's imperious question, <I>Why not the Best?</I> for his
tome's title. Now Mr. Clinton has allowed his name to be associated with
<I>Between Hope and History</I> - an allusion to the site of his birth and
the locale where he will be remembered for at least eternity. A more accurate
title might have been,<I> Between Hype and Hubris. </I>A less pretentious
alternative: <I>The Gospel According to Bill</I>.<BR>
<BR>
This canonical (or is it apocryphorical?) document, written in a style perhaps
best described as trickle-down prose, begins by reminding the Republic that
&quot;[t]his book continues the conversation I have had with the American
people about our destiny as a nation . . . The Proverbs teach us that 'Where
there is no vision, the people perish.' I ran for President in 1992 because
I thought that our nation lacked a unifying vision for our future.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
So<I> that's</I> why he did it.<BR>
<BR>
The text next informs us that The Unifying Vision consists of Opportunity,
Responsibility and Community, all of which have been heftily advanced since
that magical moment when Bill took over. He offers hard examples - facts
and statistics spinning so wildly and weirdly that it's a wonder they stay
on the page - and buttresses them with Vivid Personal Examples. I remember
in 1992 how he responded so touchingly to the pain of a thirtysomething
male who moaned out at a rally, &quot;We're your children.&quot; My personal
favorite from this text: How an immigrant hotel worker, complaining that
his son wasn't safe on the streets, asked him, &quot;If I vote for you,
will you make my boy free?&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The text does not record Mr. Clinton's response. Perhaps it ran along the
lines: &quot;Your faith has made him free. Go and sin no more.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
In short, this book is pure political pap. Sensitivity aside, Phil Gramm
could have written it. But what makes this paean to vision so repellent
is the character (as buzzy a word of the 90s as relevance was to the 60s)
of the official author.<BR>
<BR>
In <I>Boy Clinton</I>, R. Emmett Tyrrell assesses that character. Mr. Tyrrell
might fairly be described as the John Wayne of conservative journalism.
You read him to read Tyrrell; the subject is the vehicle for the star. Tyrrell
has the virtue of consistency. A 60s campus conservative and founding editor
of &quot;The American Spectator,&quot; a fine and lively rag, what you see
is what you get. <I>Boy Clinton</I> is vintage Tyrrell: a stream of reportage
and scornfest, moving with the speed of, well, white water. He views Mr.
Clinton, his missus, and their breed as no more than 60s phonies, half student
council nerds, half countercultural radicals-of-convenience, who have learned
nothing and forgotten northing . . . and whose self-righteousness blinds
them even to their own criminality. <BR>
<BR>
Writes Mr. Tyrrell: &quot;They began their public lives in the petty charlatanry
of student government and ended in the 1990s as fit objects for grand jury
inquiries, government subpoenas, congressional investigations . . . chaos
is what he and Hillary are pleased to call public service.&quot; Mr. Tyrrell
also considers matters of sexual manners and mores, drugs, cash, and truth.
He concludes by predicting the Clintons' &quot;massive rejection by the
electorate.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
And yet, massive rejection is precisely what is not happening. One reason
may be the sheer joy that Mr. Tyrrell and his legions take in trashing the
president. Mr. Tyrrell notes that, in 1992, Gennifer Flowers' charges got
lost amid the smarminess. Here they get lost amid the cleverness. And, in
a sense, Mr. Tyrrell has also learned nothing and forgotten nothing. He's
still fighting the 60s. Perhaps it's time to stop.<BR>
<BR>
And yet, the brilliant ineptitude of Mr. Tyrrell's assault - or the piteous
ineptitude of Mr. Dole's campaign - do not explain Mr. Clinton's resilience.
Jodie Allen, writing in &quot;Slate&quot; Magazine, argues that Clinton
may be the Nixon of the 90s - you hold your nose and give him his landslide.
Yet even this explanation seems inadequate. Time after time, in conversations
with liberals (especially women), people tell me that they like Mr. Clinton
because they see something of themselves in him. By conventional standards,
this would be impossible, or at least something you wouldn't want to brag
about. To what are these people relating? Certainly not his bimbos, his
draft record, his infatuation with cruise missiles, his ability to sell
you down the river (cabinet nominees, gays, welfare). Certainly not his
invocations of a morality that makes vanilla Dairy Queen positively piquant
by comparison. <BR>
<BR>
What's turning these people on?<BR>
<BR>
The answer may be as simple as it is ugly. We live in the Age of Getting
Away with It. Bill Clinton, more than any other American, Gets Away with
It. Part of this derives from the nature of politics. So many groups, so
many millions, believe they've nowhere else to go. They let him get away
with it. His personal morals may be repellent . . . but hey, who are we
to be judgmental? He gets away with it. Conservatives decry him as a pathological
liar. But hey, that's the way it is today. You know, image versus reality,
spin control. Everybody plays that game; Bill just plays it better. So he
gets away with it. And he gets away with it because he's more than the first
Baby Boomer president. He's also the first slacker president. Maureen Dowd,
writing in the &quot;New York Times,&quot; suggests that, while we may secretly
fear that we can't live up to Bob Dole's standards, we know we can meet
Bill Clinton's.<BR>
<BR>
Perhaps. But he also gets away with it as a child would. He's a spoiled
prodigy who never got over it. He's a weird, postmodern Tom Sawyer. He's
&quot;Home Alone.&quot; He's Robin Williams in &quot;Jack.&quot; And we
treat him as such.<BR>
<BR>
We may or may not be Bill Clinton's children. He's certainly our child.
The Bible predicted that a child would lead. But history indicates that,
when children try, there's little reason for hope. </BLOCKQUOTE><BR>
</H5>
<H5><CENTER>Philip Gold is a senior fellow of Seattle's Discovery Institute
and a lecturer at Georgetown University.</FONT> <BR>
<FONT SIZE=3><IMG SRC="starline2.gif" WIDTH="268" HEIGHT="20" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
<IMG SRC="ballmv.gif" WIDTH="16" HEIGHT="16" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN=
"MIDDLE"><A HREF="goldarts.html">Other articles by Philip Gold</A></CENTER>
</H5>
