<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>PC Brezhnev</TITLE>
    <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0 beta 1">
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H4>From September 5, <I>Washington Times</I> Editorial Pages</H4>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H1><CENTER>PC Enters its Brezhnev phase</CENTER>
</H1>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H4><CENTER><I>by Discovery Senior Fellow <A HREF="gold.html">Dr. Philip
Gold</A></I></CENTER>
</H4>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><CENTER><IMG SRC="/rob_c/Rob%27s%20files/DISCOVERY/goldline.gif" WIDTH=
"468" HEIGHT="7" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Great news from the Culture War. <BR>
<BR>
Political Correctness has entered its Brezhnev era. <BR>
<BR>
PC isn't dead, of course. Far from it. But the time has come to state, with
the serene certitude that only a vague metaphoric prophecy can generate,
that President Clinton (especially if re-elected) will go down in history
as the Leonid Brezhnev of PC . . . and that, five years from now, we may
be referring to the current Vice President as &quot;Goreby.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Here's what's coming down. <BR>
<BR>
The Brezhnev era (for those fortunate enough to know nothing about it) roughly
describes the Soviet Union during the twenty years between Nikita (&quot;Hare-Brained
Schemes&quot;) Khrushchev's enforced retirement and Mikhail (the original
&quot;Gorby&quot;) Gorbachev's ascent, i.e., mid-1960s to mid-1980s. The
Brezhnev clique and claque shipped Mr. K. back to his dacha for, among other
schemes, putting missiles in Cuba, wheat farms in Siberia, and venom in
the Sino-Soviet snuggle-fest. Gorby had only one hare-brained scheme: thinking
he could make communism work by giving people a taste of late 20<SUP>th</SUP>
century western alternatives (How ya gonna keep 'em down on the farm after
they've seen MTV?). But what concerns us here are the years between the
schemes, and what they tell us about the human soul. <BR>
<BR>
The Brezhnev era apparatus seemed omnipresent, invincible, expanding almost
at will. The Bolshies had also gone affluent. The future was secure. <BR>
<BR>
Yet within this structure of dominance, corruption took on a troika of forms.
The more cynical knew that the system was bankrupt, had nothing to offer,
and couldn't survive. They chose to enjoy it while it lasted. (Many have
since printed up new business cards.) The more vicious chose to exercise
power for the sake of power, in countless sterile oppressions at home, in
the construction of an utterly lunatic defense establishment, and in costly
foreign games. The more sincere and self-deluding, who still believed the
weary phrases, joined the vicious in pushing the system to what Polish dissident
Adam Michik once called the highest stage of communism: complete absurdity.
<BR>
<BR>
As for the rest, those who were neither vicious nor cynical nor self-deluding:
They went along. Later, many conceded that they had lived through a time
when theory collided with reality and lost - a time when ideological dementia
encountered sullen popular indifference, and lost to that, too. <BR>
<BR>
And so it is with PC today. The clique and claque are everywhere: the government
and courts, the universities and schools, the churches, the media, the family,
the street. But the sterility's starting to show. <BR>
<BR>
After all, once you've deconstructed everything, what's left to offer, create,
or preserve? After you've made it an article of faith that all human relationships
are based upon power, and all standards relative and oppressive, what's
to keep people from applying that notion to the explainers themselves? <BR>
<BR>
The life is gone. The PC promise of multi-cultural efflorescence and diversity
long ago segued into mere power politics. The PC promise of postmodern literature
and art and scholarship long ago sank, Marx-like, beneath its own pedantic
nihilism. And people know it, and are growing weary of it - not least of
all those young people who sit through the sensitivity training and the
screed-lectures and the rest with expressions that would not have been out
of place in Moscow, circa 1975. <BR>
<BR>
So the PC clique and claque begin to face their own Brezhnev era choices:
to take the money and power as long as it lasts; to become ever more bizarre
in their pursuits; or to just go along, evading the fact that PC suffers
from the same fatal deficiency as Marxism. It neither explains the world
adequately nor works well in it. Whether the claim be that there is only
one reality - the Marxist - or no reality at all, the net effect is the
same. <BR>
<BR>
Of course, the Soviet Union did not collapse from internal failure alone.
The United States hastened the demise in two ways. We kept the pressure
on, and we offered at least the image of alternatives. Inefficiency alone
was not enough to bring it down. There had to be a sense that something
better also existed, or could be made to exist. <BR>
<BR>
And that's how to bring down PC. Pressure and offer. Pressure the movement
toward the extremes of its own innate absurdity. It won't be hard; they're
already half-way there. Their weakness is their inability to abide any reality
(or unreality) other than their own, coupled with a lascivious desire to
exercise power for its own sake. It's an ugly combination, whether in the
courtroom or the classroom. Still, any movement that has reached the point
of claiming that the laws of physics are a sexist conspiracy can probably
be invited to prove it by jumping off the roof. <BR>
<BR>
And offer. The Republican Party and the conservative feminist movement now
terrify PC - not because they're movements of inclusion yet, but because
they could be. What might even a modest academic and literary renaissance
accomplish? PC rage nowadays has a curious quality: no longer the anger
of righteous indignation, just the shrill resentment of being challenged,
concealing - no longer completely - the beginnings of a fear that there's
nothing left inside, that perhaps there never was. <BR>
<BR>
And a fear that people might be noticing.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H4>Philip Gold is a senior fellow of the Seattle-based Discovery Institute
and a lecturer at Georgetown University. </H4>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
