<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Small Groups</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
From August 11, 1996 <I>Washington Times</I> Editorial Pages<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<H1><CENTER>Bound by Gossamer Webs of Trivia</CENTER>
</H1>
<H4><CENTER><I>by Dr. <A HREF="gold.html">Philip Gold </A></I></CENTER>
</H4>
<P><CENTER><IMG SRC="goldline.gif" WIDTH="468" HEIGHT="7" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<P>&quot;Modern American life . . . is characterized by new communities
far more numerous and far less intense than those of earlier ages.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
So wrote historian Daniel Boorstin more than 30 years ago. At the time,
he was speaking of &quot;consumption communities,&quot; and the notion that
those of similar lifestyle have more in common with each other than with
their geographical, religious, or ethnic compatriots.<BR>
<BR>
Concluded Boorstin:<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The modern American is tied &shyp; by the thinnest of threads and
the most volatile, switchable loyalties &shyp; to thousands of other Americans
by nearly everything he eats or drinks, or wears, or reads. . . . We are
held to other men, not only by a few iron bonds, but by countless gossamer
webs tying together the trivia of our lives every day.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Since then, several generations of social critics, researchers, and politicians
have made entire careers deploring the weakening, if not the outright demise,
of those few &quot;iron&quot; bonds of family, faith, community, country.
The Right, religious and non, touts the so-called traditional values that
made sense before the iron rusted. The Communitarians proffer an apolitical
return to the neighborhoods where you heard gossip about your sins on your
way back from (or to) committing them, albeit with a much-abbreviated catalogue
of sins. Most recently, political scientist Robert Putnam has decried the
&quot;Bowling Alone&quot; phenomenon: the decades-long decline in old-fashioned
voluntary group membership, and presumably therefore in sociability. And
nearly everybody, from the Christian Coalition to the Politics of Meaning
crowd, agree that this is a civilization of human beings seemingly unable
to relate to much of anything beyond the twitchings within their tummies,
their genitalia, and their skulls.<BR>
<BR>
Or maybe not.<BR>
<BR>
One of the most remarkable phenomena of the last few decades has been the
&quot;small groups&quot; movement &shyp; actually not a movement at all,
but the spontaneous rise of myriad little organizations, some <I>ad hoc</I>
and evanescent, others more permanent. Sociologist Robert Wuthnow estimates
that as many as 30 percent of all Americans may participate in such activities.
In his recent book, &quot;Sharing the Journey,&quot; he suggests that these
groups, which feature minimal levels of commitment, easy entry and exit,
and which usually concentrate on a single activity, are now a permanent
fixture of American life. A glance at the newspaper personal section will
reveal their extent: everything from Bible study to addiction recovery,
from confederations of space alien abductees to Adult Survivors of Fairly
Normal Parents. Many view these groups as little more than psychotherapeutic
and spiritual versions of Boorstin's &quot;consumption communities,&quot;
providing audiences for the empty and the self-obsessed. Wuthnow, while
acknowledging their limitations, sees them as valuable, provided they're
expected to augment, not replace, the older and larger assemblages.<BR>
<BR>
But maybe not.<BR>
<BR>
To understand the significance of the small group phenomenon, and the corresponding
decline in more permanent affiliations, it may be necessary to deep-six
two common sense notions: that small groups are trivial, and that the &quot;iron
bonds&quot; are natural. In fact, in a world of political and economic megastructures
and accelerating cultural globalization, these groups may provide a vital,
and perhaps a final, access to sanity. Perhaps they can help restore the
civility that civilization, by virtue of its scale and unnatural harshness,
takes away<BR>
<BR>
As a species, <I>homo sapiens </I>may be 100,000 to 300,000 years old. For
all but a few thousand of those years, <I>homo sapiens</I> lived in small
groups of hunter-gatherers. Evolutionary biology tells us that we are genetically
encoded for such an existence, that our genetic make-up has not changed
since the Neolithic Revolution which established sedentary civilization,
and that genetic coding includes behavioral repertoires as well as physiological
characteristics. Yes, humankind is the only species to evolve culturally.
But the fact remains: We are programmed to live in small groups.<BR>
<BR>
Yet we cannot. Even if we could, few of us would wish to return to such
a life, or endure the small group as the limit of physical survival and
social reality. &quot;Back to the Pleistocene&quot; is not an option. But,
in a world of seemingly endless impersonal and anonymous possibilities &shyp;
a world of people who often feel compelled to avail themselves of more possibilities
than might be good for them &shyp; some form of participation in small groups
makes genetic, and therefore psychological sense. The combination of right-size
and reasonable distance from others can be both therapeutic and civilizing:
indeed, more civilizing than life amid the megaliths and the masses which,
whatever their material contributions, have always been acknowledged as,
in so many other ways, dehumanizing. Small groups provide &quot;transient
stability&quot; in a world of civilized creation which inevitably gives
rise to decidedly uncivilized, and ofttimes savage behavior. <BR>
<BR>
But if this is true, or even plausible, an uneasy question arises. What
about loyalty? If conventional structures no longer command it, and if small
groups don't demand it, and if self-interest and survival no longer adhere
to anything in particular, what can hold civilization together? Will jogging
clubs and support groups, Republicans and Democrats, Star Trek conventions
and alternative Sunday schools, be enough? Can a world be maintained on
trivia?<BR>
Or would it even have to be?<BR>
<BR>
Archeology and anthropology show that small hunter-gatherer groups tend
toward the nonviolent. Their moral codes tend to be self-enforcing. Few
dare risk banishment from the group; few dare attack their sole source of
survival. Still, history shows that, ever since the species settled down
and opportunities for interactions with strangers began to increase, humans
have oppressed, tortured, and killed each other over different concepts
of what the &quot;iron bonds&quot; beyond the small group should be. Would
the spiritual and therapeutic hunter-gatherers of postmodern civilization
be willing to fight over the &quot;gossamer webs tying together the trivia
of our lives every day?&quot; It all depends, I guess, on what one considers
trivial.<BR>
<BR>
And on how many of them there are.<BR>
<HR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H4>Philip Gold is a senior fellow of the Seattle-based Discovery Institute
and a lecturer at Georgetown University.</H4>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><CENTER><BR>
<A HREF="aboutdis.html"><IMG SRC="image44.gif" WIDTH="108" HEIGHT="46" 
ALIGN="TOP" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A><A HREF="current.html"><IMG SRC="image45.gif"
WIDTH="106" HEIGHT="46" ALIGN="TOP" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A><A HREF="front.html"><IMG SRC=
"image46.gif" WIDTH="99" HEIGHT="46" ALIGN="TOP" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A><BR>
<A HREF="ggindex.html"><IMG SRC="image47.gif" WIDTH="109" HEIGHT="48" ALIGN=
"TOP" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A><A HREF="iltf.html"><IMG SRC="image48.gif"
WIDTH="105" HEIGHT="48" ALIGN="TOP" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A><A HREF="whatsnew.html"><IMG SRC=
"image49.gif" WIDTH="99" HEIGHT="48" ALIGN="TOP" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A></CENTER>
<H3><CENTER><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="image51.gif" WIDTH="147" HEIGHT=
"59" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A></CENTER>
</H3>
</BODY>
