<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE>Psychobabble Rising</TITLE></HEAD><BODY><H3><I>Insight magazine December 18, 1995<BR></I></H3><H1><CENTER>Psychobabble Rising, but we <I>Feel the Pain</I> </CENTER></H1><H3><CENTER>by <BR><I><A HREF="gold.html">Philip Gold </A></I></CENTER></H3><BR><HR>Bill and Hillary. The president who feels your pain. The presidentialpartner (n&eacute;e first lady) who informs you that you know your lifeis empty and touts the Politics of Meaning as therapy. The couple who consideropposition to their caring policies as mean-spirited, unfeeling and paranoid,and who take to the airwaves to instruct the republic on how to talk tothe kids about everything from cigarettes to the Oklahoma City bombing.<BR><BR><BR>Ever since the Clintons first entered our collective consciousness (andcollective unconscious?) both the pundits and the people have noted theirpenchant for psychologized discourse. Columnist Suzanne Fields recentlysuggested that Clinton seems to aspire to a role nowhere mentioned in theConstitution or other legislation: therapist-in-chief. Most Americans probablyhave not viewed this as anything to get paranoid, neurotic, obsessed orborderline-disordered about. After all, psychobabble is everywhere. <BR><BR><BR>And that's the problem. Psychobabble-the reduction of personal and politicaldiscourse to minimal psychologized vocabularies-is no passing fad. It is,instead, the culmination of a century-long process. And, in many ways, Clinton-aman who seems to have neither core nor anchor, and scant sensibility savefor his image of others' image of him-is an appropriate president for anation in the final stages of psychologized dysfunction. <BR><BR><HR><H3><CENTER>***Psychobabble-discourse in psychologized vocabularies-is nopassing fad.*** </CENTER></H3><HR>A little history tells a lot. <BR><BR><BR>A century or so ago, this country experienced a deep cultural crisis. Comfortableold spiritual verities were yielding to the domineering, irrefutable truthsof materialistic science. As the cities filled with the new middle classesof the corporate workforce and with millions of immigrants, once-stablesocial patterns and traditions deteriorated. America seemed destined tobecome a multicultural, amoral mess. Divorce rates were rising. Crime wasrampant. Not everybody read, or even worse, respected the same books. Allthe little issues seemed to combine into one big issue that no one couldquite define, let alone solve. <BR><BR><BR>Enter the shrinks. <BR><BR><BR>One of the salient characteristics of the so-called Progressive Era (roughlyTeddy Roosevelt to Woodrow Wilson) was the bipartisan deification of expertiseand the professionalization of just about every human activity that couldbe professionalized. Psychiatry was a profession, albeit a poorly regardedand remunerated one. Psychiatrists worked at the margins of medicine andsocial relevance, mostly in state and charitable mental hospitals and asylums.Meanwhile, in the ruts and grooves of academe, psychology was strugglingto establish itself as a separate and independent branch of human knowledge,i.e., as university departments with their own budgets and as an organizedbody of practitioners with lots of dull journals to read and pompous conventionsto attend. <BR><BR><BR>Both groups decided that respectability and affluence could be attainedby expanding their purview. Psychiatry, with a nudge or two from Freud andhis claque, decided that the whole world was sick and in need of its ministrations,whether it knew it or not. Ditto psychology, and that strange amalgam, psychotherapy,was born. <BR><BR><BR>(Scientifically speaking, there is no such thing as psychotherapy, onlya melange of competing theories and practices. Imagine a chemistry thatcontained 50 different definitions of a molecule.)<BR><BR><BR><BR>The therapists also decided that they could be of inestimable value by insertingthemselves and their notions into the workings of every aspect of the stateand on behalf of causes that appealed to them personally. So these new expertson the human spirit began peddling their wares everywhere they could findcustomers. <BR><BR><BR>And find them they did-in social work, the juvenile- and criminal-justicesystems, in education and the other disciplines, among the clergy, the literati,the artistes. Some worked out of universities; other found employment withthe government or the private sector, teaching corporations how to manufacturedocile workers and ardent consumers, helping the government hype its warsand policies and generally convincing the populace that theirs was the kingdomand the truth. <BR><BR><BR>By the 1950s, few Americans could find a mate, raise their kids, confronttheir troubles or know what to feel without seeking, or being affected by,these experts. In the 1960s, politics itself became psychologized-protestbecame a form of growth and fulfillment and the issue protested matteredless than the protest. Jimmy Carter probably was the first president whosemajor attractiveness was his therapeutic value. Feminism devolved into the-personal-is-politicalschtick of consciousness-raising and if-I-feel-oppressed-I-must-be. Nukeshad to go because they upset the kids. Welfare is good because it's caringand compassionate. Ecological legislation will help restore our global consciousnessand that is the primary goal, regardless of the real-world effects. <BR><BR><BR>Then came the talk shows. And the recovery books. And the &quot;abuse excuse&quot;in law. And the Clintons, who, like so many of their generational and politicalconfreres, insist on judging policies by their intent and not their results,and who attack their opponents' emotions, not their ideas. Thomas Sowellsees this as the fundamental characteristic-and perhaps weakness-of theliberal self-anointed. <BR><BR><BR>Psychologized discourse has been around for a century. It has had a centuryto prove that it can't deliver. It's not just that if heart surgeons hadthe same success rate as psychotherapists, they'd all be in prison. It'sthat a civilization in thrall to the psychological can't work. It createspeople who can conceive of themselves only as isolated units with the outerworld important only as a source of frustration or gratification. It createsa politics in which emotions become the goal, not the fuel. It makes rationaldiscourse impossible. <BR><BR><BR>And Bill Clinton represents the final stage of this deterioration. It isreported that, in his latest incarnation, he intends to campaign in 1996by portraying the Republicans as &quot;heartless.&quot; <BR><BR><BR>Democrat or Republican-do you like this form of governance? <BR><BR><BR>In your politics? In your courts? In your culture? In your private lives?And in your souls? <BR><P><CENTER><B><I>Philip Gold is a senior fellow of the Seattle-based DiscoveryInstitute and a lecturer at Georgetown University. </I></B></CENTER><P><HR><H2><CENTER><A HREF="1995view.html">Discovery Views</A><BR><A HREF="journal.html">Discovery Journals<BR></A><A HREF="inquiry.html">Discovery Inquiry</A></CENTER></H2><H3><CENTER><A HREF="index.html"><BR><IMG SRC="discoimg.gif" WIDTH="219" HEIGHT="93" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN=middle>Discovery Homee</A></CENTER></H3></BODY></HTML>
