<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Chambers biography</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><CENTER><IMG SRC="ship.gif" WIDTH="67" HEIGHT="61" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
Ray B. Chambers</CENTER>
</H1>
<H3><CENTER><I>Fellow</I> </CENTER>
</H3>
<P><CENTER><IMG SRC="barrwb.gif" WIDTH="512" HEIGHT="5" ALIGN="BOTTOM" 
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></CENTER>
<P>Ray Chambers, Fellow of Discovery Institute, advocates and promotes the
practicality of bringing high speed rail to America with a practical emphasis
on privatizing all or part of the passenger rail system. His work also examines
<A HREF="chmbrinq.html">the need for a National High Speed Rail Plan</A>.
Chambers, who is Chairman of Chambers, Conlon &amp; Hartwell, Inc., in Washington
D.C., is a <B>former Director of Congressional Relations for the U.S. Department
of Transportation</B>. He is also former Deputy and Acting Assistant Secretary
of Health, Education and Welfare. He served for eight years as an Administrative
Assistant in the U.S. House of Representatives. <BR>
<BR>
While with the U.S. DOT Mr. Chambers was responsible for all legislative
strategy associated with the passage of the <B>Regional Rail Reorganization
Act of 1973 </B>and the<B> Railroad Revitalization and Regulatory Reform
Act of 1976</B>. These laws were responsible for restructuring the major
bankrupt freight railroads in the United States, including the creation
of Conrail. <BR>
<BR>
On behalf of transportation clients, he has been heavily involved with all
major railroad legislation since leaving the U.S. DOT in 1976. He holds
a B.A. degree from the Redlands University and an M.A. from Rutgers University.
<BR>
<P><CENTER><IMG SRC="barrwb.gif" WIDTH="512" HEIGHT="5" ALIGN="BOTTOM" 
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></CENTER>
<H3><CENTER><A HREF="discofel.html">LIST OF FELLOWS</A></CENTER>
</H3>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="aboutdis.html"><IMG SRC="image44.gif" WIDTH="108"
