<H3><I>From the Fall 1995 Discovery Journal:</I></H3>
<H1><CENTER><I>Visible Man</I> making new appearances </CENTER>
</H1>
<BR>
<A HREF="gildrbio.html">George Gilder's </A>conservative cult classic, <I>Visible
Man</I>, is gaining attention in the midst of intense debates over welfare
reform and racism. Republication of <I>Visible Man</I>  is nothing if not
timely. <BR>
<BR>
In <I>Visible Man</I>, Gilder tells the the true story of Sam, a black youth
of the Albany ghetto, and the women in his disconnected life. For Gilder,
Sam is not a victim of racism, but the all-too conspicuous victim of government
policy. As the message of<I>Visible Man</I>  spreads the popularity of the
book seems to pick up momentum. <BR>
<BR>
Speaker of the House Newt Gingrich's monthly newsletter, &quot;Renewing
American Civilization,&quot; will feature <I>Visible Man </I>as the cover
article in November, and the book has been chosen as a monthly selection
for the newsletter's reader's circle. Gingrich, also has expressed interest
in including <I>Visible Man</I>  in the curriculum for his &quot;Renewing
American Civilization&quot; college course in 1996. Currently Reader's Digest
is considering publication of <I>Visible Man</I>  in a condensed form. In
August, Michael Medved had Gilder as a special guest on the Rush Limbaugh
radio program, which Medved guest-hosted while Limbaugh was on vacation.
<A HREF="bookordr.html">If you are interested in obtaining a copy of <I>Visible
Man</I>  for only $15.95, click here.</A> <BR>
