<HTML><HEAD>  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">  <TITLE>Creation-Evolution Controversies</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><P><CENTER><A HREF="crscfellows.html"><IMG SRC="felcrsc.gif" WIDTH="65"HEIGHT="32" ALIGN="BOTTOM" NATURALSIZEFLAG="2" BORDER="0"></A><A HREF="crscarts.html"><IMG SRC="artscrsc.gif" WIDTH="65" HEIGHT="32" ALIGN="BOTTOM" NATURALSIZEFLAG="2"BORDER="0"></A><A HREF="aboutcrsc.html"><IMG SRC="aboutcrsc.gif" WIDTH="65" HEIGHT="32" ALIGN="BOTTOM" NATURALSIZEFLAG="2" BORDER="0"></A></CENTER></P><P><CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=+3>Issues in the creation-evolution controversies</FONT></B></CENTER></P><P><CENTER><FONT SIZE=-1>by<BR><A HREF="/Articles%20by%20Jonathan%20Wells/Creation-Evolution/wells.html">DiscoveryFellow, Jonathan Wells</A><BR>Ph.D. (Theology), Yale University<BR>Ph.D. (Biology), University of California at Berkeley</FONT></CENTER></P><P>&nbsp;</P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P><CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=-1>This article appeared in the January 1996 issue  of and is reprinted with permission from <I>The World &amp; I</I>, a publication  of The Washington Times Corporation, copyright &copy; 1996.</FONT></B></CENTER></P></BLOCKQUOTE><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P><B><FONT SIZE=+2>D</FONT>arwin's theory of evolution has produced </B>more  widespread and bitter controversy than any other theory in the history  of Western science. Except for the infamous condemnation of Galileo by  the medieval Catholic Church, there wasn't much fuss over Copernicus's  heliocentric theory of the solar system. Or Harvey's theory of the circulation  of the blood, or Newton's theory of gravitation, or Mendel's theory of  biological inheritance, or Einstein's theory of relativity. Only Darwin's  theory has provoked radical and enduring differences of opinion among large  numbers of people. Even now, almost a century and a half after it was first  proposed, it continues to be the focus of heated scientific disagreements,  bitterly contested court cases, and politically charged school board debates.</P>  <P>What is at stake in the creation-evolution controversies, and why do  they generate so much passion? What are the prospects for a resolution?</P>  <P>At the heart of the controversies is the question of our own origin:  Where did we come from, and why are we here? This question is important  because the answer to it affects how we lead our lives. Central to every  culture is an account of origins - and the creation-evolution controversies  represent the collision of two radically different accounts, each competing  for the minds of our children.</P>  <P>One reason the creation-evolution controversies have proven so difficult  to resolve is that they involve a number of very distinct issues, - some  primarily theological and some primarily scientific, - which are often  confused with each other. What follows is an attempt to sort out some of  these issues, place them in their historical context, and evaluate their  relative importance in the debate.</P>  <P>Not only are there many distinct issues, but there are also many parties  to the debate. For example, there are young-earth creationists who believe  that all things were created in approximately their present form a few  thousand years ago; there are other creationists who accept the geological  time scale but reject the notion that all living things are descended by  natural mechanisms from a common ancestor; there are theistic evolutionists  who accept common descent and evolution by natural mechanisms but maintain  that God acted through those mechanisms; there are evolutionists who see  no need for God's involvement but question one or more aspects of Darwin's  theory; and there are other evolutionists who substantially agree with  Darwin's theory and its atheistic implications. Even these five categories  (which, like most categories, are somewhat artificial) do not do justice  to the complexity of the controversies, but they will help to illustrate  it as the issues are laid out below.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>**********</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>THEOLOGICAL ISSUES</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Chronology</P>  <P>According to Darwin's theory, all plants and animals have gradually  evolved from one or a few primitive life forms by the natural selection  of random variations. This process would require vast periods of time,  - at least hundreds of millions of years. According to Genesis 1, however,  God created the world in only six days; and if one adds up the time allotted  for other events in the Old Testament, one finds only about 4,000 years  between the creation of the world and the birth of Jesus. Clearly, Darwin's  theory conflicts with a literal reading of biblical chronology.</P>  <P>Suprisingly, this conflict played almost no role in the nineteenth-century  debates over evolution. Thirty years before Darwin published <I>The </I>Origin  of Species in 1859, geologists had already found convincing evidence that  the earth was much older than 6,000 years. Most Christians accepted the  evidence and modified their interpretation of scripture accordingly. Some  allowed for a gap of undetermined duration between the six days of creation  and subsequent events, while others interpreted the Genesis days as symbols  of long ages. The gap theory departed less from a literal reading, but  the day-age theory was more consistent with the scientific evidence, and  by 1859 the latter was widely accepted even among conservative Christians.</P>  <P>Even the American fundamentalists of the 1920's, for the most part,  did not insist on a literal interpretation of biblical chronology. In the  Scopes &quot;monkey trial&quot; of 1925, creationist lawyer William Jennings  Bryan announced that he accepted the antiquity of the earth and the day-age  interpretation of Genesis. It was not until the 1960's that biblical chronology  rose to prominence in the creation-evolution controversies, largely through  the influence of engineer Henry Morris and the Institute for Creation Research  in San Diego.</P>  <P>Today, many young-earth creationists feel that the word of God has been  so adulterated by modern criticism that nothing short of defending its  literal truth will suffice. Some of these (such as Morris) consider Genesis  a testable scientific theory, and call themselves &quot;scientific creationists.&quot;  Other young-earth creationists are less concerned with biblical literalism  than with the goodness of creation: if all evils are due to the fall of  Adam and Eve, then the extinctions we see in the fossil record must be  more recent.</P>  <P>A major difficulty for young-earth creationists is that geological chronology  is based on several independent lines of scientific evidence. By observing  the rates at which sediments are presently being deposited and then measuring  the thickness of older sedimentary rocks, geologists can estimate how long  it took for those rocks to form. Also, when geologists find radioactive  elements and their decay products in rocks they can measure their ratios  and estimate probable ages from observed radioactive decay rates.</P>  <P>Young-earth creationists object that such estimates assume that rates  of sedimentation and radioactive decay have remained constant, - assumptions  which are impossible to verify empirically. Evolutionists (and many creationists)  dismiss these objections as unwarranted and implausible, and maintain that  geological chronology is scientifically well-established.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Providence</P>  <P>For Christian theists, God not only created the world but also continues  to sustain it and govern it, - an affirmation known as the doctrine of  providence. During the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries, however, some  Enlightenment philosophers (known as &quot;deists&quot;) maintained that  after the initial creation God turned the world loose to run by itself,  like a machine.</P>  <P>Deism has profound theological implications. If God is necessary only  to account for the initial creation of the universe, then all subsequent  phenomena, - even the events of human history, - are explicable without  reference to God. Jesus may have been an extraordinary person, but the  incarnation was a myth. Prayer may be psychologically comforting, but otherwise  has no effect. If God has turned the creation loose to run by itself, then  Christianity loses its doctrine of providence, - and much of its religious  content.</P>  <P>But theism has profound scientific implications. If the natural order  is subject to divine control or intervention, then worldly phenomena cannot  be completely explained without reference to God. Most scientists in Darwin's  day were theists; they relied on natural laws to explain ordinary phenomena  and the results of their experiments, but considered some things (such  as human origins and biblical miracles) beyond the reach of naturalistic  explanation. When Darwin proposed that the Creator originally breathed  life into one or a few forms and then left them to evolve by natural processes,  he encountered significant opposition from theistic scientists. Geologist  Charles Lyell, who championed the idea that natural history could be explained  by the uniform operation of natural causes, and biologist Alfred Russel  Wallace, who proposed a theory of evolution similar to Darwin's, both insisted  that the origin of human beings was a special case requiring divine intervention.</P>  <P>Today the majority of biologists are atheists who believe that God does  not exist and that naturalistic explanations are sufficient. Yet a significant  number of biologists still consider themselves theists. Most are not young-earth  creationists, but instead accept geological chronology and either (1) acknowledge  the operation of natural laws in ordinary phenomena but believe that the  history of life included successive creative acts by God, or (2) acknowledge  the uninterrupted operation of natural laws but believe that God somehow  works through those laws. Examples of the first include physicist Alan  Hayward and geologist John Wiester, and examples of the second include  physicist Howard Van Till and biologist Terry Gray. For the sake of discussion,  the first group can be called successive creationists and the second theistic  evolutionists, though not everyone would agree with these labels. Successive  creationists and theistic evolutionists are less likely to be found in  the Institute for Creation Research than in the American Scientific Affiliation,  a large organization of Christians who are also scientists.</P>  <P>Science, as it is now generally understood, is limited to naturalistic  explanations which can be empirically tested. Both successive creationists  and theistic evolutionists acknowledge this &quot;methodological naturalism,&quot;  but disagree over its applicability. Creationists criticize theistic evolutionists  for applying it to all phenomena without reservation, and thus abandoning  the doctrine of providence and being deists in disguise. Theistic evolutionists  reply that they continue to affirm God's providential control of natural  processes, even those which appear to be random. Creationists object that  this affirmation adds nothing to naturalistic explanations, and is thus  meaningless. Theistic evolutionists respond that successive creationists  tie Christian belief to a &quot;God of the gaps&quot; who is constantly  forced to retreat in the face of scientific progress.</P>  <P>Both groups, of course, reject metaphysical naturalism (the philosophical  doctrine that God does not exist and nature is all there is), but creationists  argue that the methodological naturalism of the theistic evolutionists  is practically indistinguishable from metaphysical naturalism. Creationists  thus charge theistic evolutionists with being accommodationists who let  themselves be used by atheists to make Darwinism more palatable to Christians.  Theistic evolutionists, however, see themselves as defending the reasonableness  of Christianity in a culture dominated by science.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Design</P>  <P>One of the most fundamental doctrines in Christianity is that God created  the universe by design, according to a pre-conceived plan. According to  the Bible, God created us in His image. Regardless of whether He was continually  involved in providential history (theism), or left the world to evolve  on its own (deism), God intended from the start to produce human beings  as the final outcome.</P>  <P>As a student Darwin had studied William Paley's <I>Natural Theology</I>  (1802), which argued that someone who finds a watch on the ground can logically  infer that it was made by a watchmaker. Paley's argument from design was  intended to prove the existence of God, but Darwin argued that what seemed  to be design in living organisms was really due to random variations and  survival of the fittest. In Darwin's view all species are contingent, and  as the latest product of an inherently contingent process the human species  is the most contingent of all.</P>  <P>When botanist Asa Gray suggested that God guided evolution by designing  variations, Darwin rejected the idea. In his 1868 <I>Variation of </I>Animals  and Plants Under Domestication, Darwin argued that biological variations  are like the stones which an architect finds at the base of a cliff and  assembles into a house. Although each stone is shaped by natural law, in  regard to the use to which they may be put their shapes are accidental.</P>  <P>Darwin's exclusion of design goes beyond the deistic claim that evolution  is due solely to natural processes. Theistic evolutionists (even if they  are deists on the question of providence, as their creationist critics  allege) affirm as Christians that human beings are designed by God. Therefore,  they either attribute evolution to non-Darwinian mechanisms or they accept  Darwin's theory but reject his anti-teleological interpretation of it.  Just as Darwin argued that features which appear to be designed are actually  contingent, so theistic evolutionists argue (like Asa Gray) that variations  which appear to be random are actually designed.</P>  <P>The most vocal advocates of design in the creation-evolution controversies,  however, are creationists rather than theistic evolutionists. The creationists's  arguments sometimes resemble Paley's; that is, design in living organisms  is used to prove the existence of God. Evolutionists object that such arguments  are unscientific because they invoke the supernatural, and point out that  Paley's teleological proof for God's existence has been discredited on  philosophical and theological grounds.</P>  <P>But there is a deeper issue involved. As John Henry Newman put it, Christians  believe in design because they believe in God, not in a God because they  see design. Christians may believe in God for any number of reasons (such  as faith in the Bible, or personal religious experiences); their belief  in God then leads them to the conclusion that living things are designed.  Darwin's theory denies that conclusion, and thus logically denies God's  existence.</P>  <P>In other words, the issue is not whether one can infer God from design,  but whether one can infer design in living things at all. Accordingly some  design advocates, more sophisticated than Paley, focus on design alone.  They point out that design inferences deal with agency, not with the supernatural,  and thus are not inherently unscientific. For example, a jury is not being  unscientific when it infers design in the commission of a crime. This approach  to design is used in the biology textbook <I>Of Pandas and People </I>(1993),  which has provoked heated controversy in some school districts. Critics  continue to object that design inferences cannot scientifically be applied  to living things, since only a supernatural agent could have designed them;  but design advocates counter that the nature of the designer is a separate  issue.</P>  <P>Meanwhile, evolutionists argue (like Darwin) that one can infer the  absence of design from biological evidence. Paleontologist George Gaylord  Simpson concludes in <I>The Meaning of Evolution</I> (1967) that the facts  of evolution show man to be the result of a purposeless process that did  not have him in mind. The subtitle of zoologist Richard Dawkins's <I>The  Blind </I>Watchmaker (1986) is &quot;Why the evidence of evolution reveals  a universe without design.&quot; Creationists such as law professor Phillip  E. Johnson object that using biological evidence to argue against design  or a designer is no more scientific than arguing for design or a designer,  and charge evolutionists with misusing science as a platform for their  atheistic beliefs.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Summary of the Theological Issues</P>  <P>Although biblical chronology is the most publicized theological issue  in the creation-evolution controversies, it is not the most central. Many  creationists and theistic evolutionists criticize young-earthers for their  stand on chronology, arguing that it is theologically unnecessary as well  as empirically untenable. A more important issue is whether God continues  to be providentially involved in the creation, or has turned it loose to  run by itself. Creationists insist that providence implies God's intervention  in natural events, while theistic evolutionists maintain that God's providence  underlies the natural causes which account for all pheneomena.</P>  <P>Even more important than providence is the issue of design. Christians  believe that the world was purposefully created, and that human beings  are the culmination of God's purpose. Creationists and theistic evolutionists  may disagree on other issues, but they are united in rejecting the Darwinian  claim that human beings are undesigned. By far the most important theological  question in the creation-evolution controversies is whether we are the  accidental by-product of purposeless mechanisms which did not have us in  mind, or the designed result of God's plan for creation.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>**********</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>SCIENTIFIC ISSUES</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Genetics</P>  <P>Darwin observed that members of the same species differ from each other  in slight but sometimes significant ways. A breeder makes good use of these  differences by mating only those individuals with desirable characteristics.  After several generations such selection can produce dramatically different  breeds, and Darwin reasoned that if the process were extended indefinitely  it could produce separate species.</P>  <P>Darwin's theory required that the desired traits be heritable by the  offspring of the selected individuals. But he lacked a theory of heredity  to explain how this could happen, so his theory initially encountered opposition  from other scientists. Even after the re-discovery of Mendelian genetics  in 1900 Darwin's theory languished, since genetic mutations then seemed  to render natural selection unnecessary. Only in the 1920's and 1930's  did biologists successfully combine Mendelian genetics and Darwinian evolution,  and by the 1940's Darwin's theory re-emerged in the form of a &quot;modern  synthesis.&quot;</P>  <P>According to the modern synthesis: (1) organisms are composed of genetically  determined traits; (2) if a trait confers an advantage in the competition  for survival its gene is more likely than others to be transmitted to the  next generation; therefore (3) over the course of many generations the  advantageous gene (and its corresponding trait) will be found in a higher  proportion of individuals. In other words, evolution is explained as a  change in gene frequencies due to differential survival (i.e., natural  selection). The discovery of the structure and function of DNA in the 1950's  bolstered the modern synthesis by providing a molecular explanation for  how genes could determine traits, be inherited, and mutate to produce new  variations. Given its elegant simplicity and capacity to integrate evidence  from several fields, the modern synthesis continues to be widely accepted.</P>  <P>Nevertheless, a significant number of biologists find it inadequate.  In the 1970's geneticist Richard Lewontin reported that molecular analyses  of gene products in closely related species of fruit flies revealed no  correlation between gene frequencies and morphological differences. As  a result, some biologists (including Lewontin) are convinced that evolution  cannot be explained simply by changes in gene frequencies.</P>  <P>Some critics of the modern synthesis point out that artificial selection  reaches a limit beyond which no further change can be effected; even after  many generations of breeding, a dog is still a dog. Even if the theory  can explain small-scale &quot;microevolution&quot; within a single species  or between closely related species, some biologists doubt whether it can  explain large-scale &quot;macroevolution&quot; such as the emergence of  new body plans (e.g., vertebrates and invertebrates) or structural novelties  (e.g., eyes and wings). In the 1950's geneticist Richard Goldschmidt argued  that macroevolution could not be due to the gradual accumulation of small  changes but had to be the result of macromutations which produce large  changes in a single generation. Goldschmidt's ideas were not well received  at the time, but are now popular among some biologists (such as Stephen  Jay Gould) who doubt that the modern synthesis can explain macroevolution.  Other critics of Darwinian macroevolution (such as embryologist Brian Goodwin)  see complexity theory as a promising alternative.</P>  <P>The distinction between microevolution and macroevolution is important  in the creation-evolution controversies. According to the Bible, God created  the major types of living things (such as grass, trees, birds, whales,  cattle and people), but left open the possibility of diversification within  those major types. Therefore, most creationists have little or no problem  with microevolution, even when it is attributed to selective changes in  gene frequencies. The most celebrated example of Darwinian microevolution,  diversification of finch beaks on the Galapagos Islands, poses a challenge  only to those young-earth creationists who dispute the amount of time involved.  The second most celebrated example of microevolution, a change in the proportion  of light- and dark-colored moths due to industrial pollution in England,  doesn't even pose this challenge, since it occurred within our lifetime.</P>  <P>Major theological problems arise only when microevolution is extrapolated  to macroevolution. If all aspects of living things are due to changes in  gene frequencies resulting from differential survival, then features which  creationists attribute to design are reduced to products of natural mechanisms  which exclude design. But as creationists are quick to point out, the extrapolation  of Darwinian microevolution to macroevolution is rejected even by many  non-theistic biologists.</P>  <P>Such biologists, however, usually object to having their views cited  in defense of creationist arguments. They protest that although they may  doubt a particular theory of the process of macroevolution they do not  doubt the overall pattern of macroevolution. In their view the best alternative  to the modern synthesis is not creationism, but some form of non-Darwinian  evolution. According to theistic as well as non-theistic evolutionists,  the integrity of the scientific enterprise requires biologists to exclude  creationist explanations and persevere in their search for natural mechanisms.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Fossils</P>  <P>One important source of evidence for the pattern of macroevolution is  the fossil record, which shows clearly that the earth was once populated  by organisms different from those now living. According to Darwin, the  history of life is like a branching tree, with one or a few primitive forms  at its base and extant forms at the tips of its branches. Darwin's theory  implies that there are numerous transitional forms linking the various  stages in the history of life, but nineteenth-century scientists objected  that fossils of those transitional forms had not been found. Darwin anticipated  this objection, and attributed the absence of transitional forms to the  widely acknowledged imperfection of the fossil record. Many forms may not  have been preserved in the first place, and many which were preserved may  have been destroyed by subsequent erosion.</P>  <P>Subsequent fossil-collecting has turned up some species with features  intermediate between previously-known fossils or living organisms (e.g.,  birds with reptile-like teeth), and many evolutionary biologists are convinced  that the fossil record has confirmed Darwin's theory. Other biologists,  however, have come to the opposite conclusion: they are convinced that  the fossil record shows Darwin's model of gradual transitions to be largely  incorrect. According to paleontologists Stephen Jay Gould and Niles Eldredge,  the fossil record exhibits a pattern of &quot;punctuated equilibria&quot;  - fossils appear suddenly, persist unchanged for a time, then disappear.  The most dramatic example is the sudden appearance of most major categories  of living things in the early Cambrian (the first rocks in which abundant  fossils occur), but the same phenomenon occurs even on a smaller scale.</P>  <P>The theory of punctuated equilibria has convinced some biologists that  non-Darwinian mechanisms must be responsible for most fossil patterns.  Darwinian evolutionists maintain, however, that the absence of transitional  forms can still be explained by the imperfecton of the fossil record. Furthermore,  they argue, it would be theoretically possible for a new species to arise  fairly quickly through changes in gene frequencies if small numbers of  organisms became geographically isolated from the rest of the population;  upon returning to the original habitat, this new species would then seem  to appear suddenly in the fossil record. In other words, it is possible  to accept punctuated equilibria without abandoning Darwin's theory.</P>  <P>Creationists frequently cite punctuated equilibria in their arguments  against Darwinian evolution; some go so far as to claim that the fossil  evidence supports a creation model over Darwin's branching-tree model.  Like biologists who reject Darwinian macroevolution, however, biologists  who accept punctuated equilibria do not like to be used in support of creationist  arguments. They point out that they still agree on the fact of common descent,  which is the essential point of Darwin's branching tree model. Creationists  counter that the issue is not whether evolutionists agree on common descent,  but whether the evidence supports it. Evolutionists (theistic as well as  non-theistic) reply that common descent is the only scientific alternative  to divine intervention, and argue that it has been empirically established  on other grounds.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Homology</P>  <P>Biologists systematically classify organisms on the basis of their similarities  and dissimilarities. One has to be careful in choosing which similarities  to use, however; bats and butterflies use wings to fly through the air,  and whales and lobsters use horizontal tail flippers to propel themselves  through water, but classifying bats with butterflies and whales with lobsters  would overlook anatomical and physiological features which biologists consider  more important.</P>  <P>In the decades before Darwin's <I>Origin of Species</I>, biologists  used &quot;homology&quot; to refer to features which are structurally similar  even though they may perform dissimilar functions in different organisms  (such as the forelimbs of bats and whales), and &quot;analogy&quot; to  refer to features which perform similar functions in different organisms  but are structurally dissimilar (such as the wings of bats and butterflies).  Homologies justified similar classification, while analogies did not. The  resulting classification scheme was interpreted as a reflection of God's  plan for creation.</P>  <P>In Darwin's theory, however, the same classification scheme was re-interpreted  as the result of descent with modification. According to Darwin, the forelimbs  of bats and whales are similar not because they are created according to  a common plan but because they are inherited from a common ancestor. He  acknowledged that this did not resolve all cases of disputed classification,  but proposed that when in doubt the best guide is embryology; he considered  the common ancestry of the vertebrates, for example, to be demonstrated  by the striking similarity of their embryos at an early stage of development.</P>  <P>After 1859 homology was re-defined to mean similarity by common descent,  and many biologists turned from mere classification to the reconstruction  of &quot;phylogenies,&quot; or evolutionary histories of related organisms.  With the advent of molecular biology in the mid-twentieth century, DNA  sequences were added to the list of features which biologists could analyze  for homologies. Although (with rare and fragmentary exceptions) DNA is  available only from living organisms, it has become an important tool in  studying evolutionary patterns.</P>  <P>Some biologists, however, criticize the whole enterprise of inferring  ancestor-descendant relationships from similarities and dissimilarities.  In the 1960's some evolutionists (later dubbed &quot;cladists&quot;) argued  that according to Darwin's theory significant evolutionary changes occur  only when two lineages branch off from each other. Application of this  approach eventually led a few cladists to conclude that similarities and  differences among organisms can tell us nothing at all about ancestor-descendant  relationships. These &quot;transformed cladists&quot; (such as zoologist  Colin Patterson) are now critical of all attempts to reconstruct phylogenies  on the basis of homology.</P>  <P>Other biologists (mostly embryologists such as Brian K. Hall) criticize  the concept of homology itself. They point out that there are now at least  three definitions of the word: morphological homology (based on structural  similarity), phylogenetic homology (based on common descent), and embryological  homology (based on similarity of developmental pathways). Often, features  which are homologous by one definition are not homologous by the other  two. For example, octopus eyes and human eyes are structurally similar  but they are not derived from a common ancestral eye and their developmental  pathways are different, so they are morphologically homologous but phylogenetically  and embryologically non-homologous. Vertebrate forelimbs exhibit similar  skeletal patterns which are presumed to be inherited from a common ancestor,  yet their detailed developmental pathways are different, making them morphologically  and phylogenetically homologous but embryologically non-homologous.</P>  <P>Since phylogenetic homology presupposes common descent and thus cannot  be used to prove it, and since morphological and embryological homology  so often fail to coincide, inferring ancestor-descendant relationships  from homology is fraught with difficulties. Some creationists point to  these difficulties to demonstrate that the evidence for common descent  is disputed. Evolutionists respond that they remain convinced of common  descent, and challenge creationists to come up with a scientific alternative  which does not invoke divine creation. Creationists counter that this begs  the question, since the issue is whether naturalistic explanations are  adequate or need to be supplemented by explanations based on design and  creation. Evolutionists (theistic as well as non-theistic) reply that acts  of God have no place in science.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Summary of the Scientific Issues</P>  <P>According to the modern synthesis, evolution is caused by a change in  gene frequencies due to natural selection. Some biologists consider this  sufficient to account for all aspects of evolution, while others consider  it inadequate, especially as an account of large-scale macroevolution.  Despite this dispute over the process of evolution most biologists consider  the pattern of evolution to be well-established, primarily by evidence  from the fossil record and homology. Nevertheless, some biologists question  whether the pattern in the fossil record conforms to Darwin's gradualist  model of the history of life, while others question the use of homologies  to reconstruct ancestor-descendant relationships. Even these critics of  evolutionary theory, however, generally agree that living things are descended  from a common ancestor by natural mechanisms.</P>  <P>Creationists often cite disagreements among biologists to show that  Darwinian evolution is untrue, or at least unproved; some go so far as  to claim that the evidence demonstrates divine creation instead. Most biologists,  however, object to being used in support of creationist arguments, pointing  out that they all agree on common descent by natural mechanisms. Furthermore,  they argue, the integrity of the scientific enterprise requires them to  exclude divine intervention and rely on natural mechanisms to explain the  history of life.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>**********</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P><B>PROSPECTS FOR RESOLUTION</B></P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>Various polls have shown that only about 10% of the American people  accept Darwinian evolution; the remaining 90% are almost evenly divided  between young-earth creationists and those who believe that God was the  guiding force in the history of life. In other words, the vast majority  of Americans believe that we are the designed result of God's creative  activity, and that we should conduct our lives accordingly. Yet the only  view of human origins that can legally be taught in public schools is that  we are accidental by-products of purposeless natural processes, with survival  being the main criterion for how we conduct our lives. The ensuing controversies  are not only about creation and evolution, but also about who gets to teach  what to our children.</P>  <P>How can the controversies be resolved? Scientific creationists think  they can resolve them by requiring that Genesis be taught alongside Darwinian  evolution as a scientific theory. But this is unlikely to work, not only  because the courts prohibit it as an establishment of religion, but also  because it flies in the face of the available evidence and the way a great  many Christians interpret scripture. Some Darwinians think they can resolve  the controversies by calling evolution a fact. But this is unlikely to  carry the day, because except for the facts that (1) living things today  are different from those in the past and (2) it is possible to modify a  species by selection, virtually all of the evidence is interpreted in conflicting  ways among biologists themselves. Any reasonably neutral observer can see  that Darwinian macroevolution is a disputed theory, not an empirical fact.</P>  <P>When evolutionists say they agree on the &quot;fact&quot; of evolution,  they generally mean they agree on common descent and evolution by natural  mechanisms. Their conflicting interpretations of the evidence, however,  show that this agreement is at the level of philosophical commitment rather  than empirical inference. Like all scientists they share a commitment to  methodological naturalism: scientific explanations must exclude supernatural  causes and rely entirely on natural mechanisms. But unlike most pre-Darwinian  scientists, evolutionists believe that naturalistic explanations can account  for all phenomena in the history of life (even though we may not yet have  those explanations in hand).</P>  <P>Theistic evolutionists hope to resolve the controversies by affirming  this extension of methodological naturalism without surrendering belief  in God. But this is unlikely to work, because once they grant naturalistic  explanations such unlimited scope most of their non-theistic colleagues  regard their theistic beliefs as harmless and irrelevant, while most of  their creationist colleagues regard them as deists and accommodationists.</P>  <P>So although theistic evolutionists see themselves as mediators, they  do not occupy the common ground which could, potentially, resolve the creation-evolution  controversies.</P>  <P>What is that common ground? One feature of it must be, certainly, the  non-establishment of religion. Fortunately, all parties to the controversies  acknowledge the value of this. Even scientific creationists, who are regarded  by evolutionists as attempting to establish Christian fundamentalism, are  primarily rebelling against the establishment of atheism. As evolution  is currently taught in public schools, it frequently includes the claim  that we are accidental by-products of purposeless processes that did not  have us in mind. By any standard this claim has religious content, yet  the opposite viewpoint is systematically excluded from the classroom on  the grounds that it is religious rather than scientific. But evolutionists  who want to argue against divine purpose while claiming constitutional  immunity from counterarguments are like tennis players who won't let their  opponents hit the ball; eventually, the spectators and referees are going  to throw them off the court. If they want to continue teaching evolutionary  biology without creationist interference, then they would do well to avoid  theology.</P>  <P>Another feature of the common ground is limited methodological naturalism.  All parties to the creation-evolution controversies acknowledge the value  of explanations based on natural mechanisms; not even scientific creationists  expect biologists to attribute experimental results to divine intervention.  Methodological naturalism does not generate controversy, - only its axiomatic  extension to all phenomena, past as well as present. Students must be taught  that science is the search for naturalistic explanations, - it would be  a serious disservice to teach them otherwise, - but does that mean they  must be taught that science is omnipotent? Perhaps it would be wiser to  rear them to be like the great scientists of the past, who cultivated a  profound respect for the limits of their discipline and the limitless mystery  of the cosmos.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P><P><CENTER><A HREF="aboutdis.html"><IMG SRC="aboutdis.gif" WIDTH="107" HEIGHT="46" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><A HREF="current.html"><IMG SRC="image45.gif" WIDTH="106" HEIGHT="46" ALIGN="MIDDLE" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A><AHREF="front.html"><IMG SRC="image46.gif" WIDTH="99" HEIGHT="46" ALIGN="MIDDLE"NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A><BR><A HREF="ggindex.html"><IMG SRC="image47.gif" WIDTH="109" HEIGHT="48" ALIGN="MIDDLE" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A><A HREF="whatsnew.html"><IMG SRC="image49.gif"WIDTH="99" HEIGHT="48" ALIGN="MIDDLE" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A><BR><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="image51.gif" WIDTH="147" HEIGHT="59" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
